      <emotional-journey>
        <reasoning>POV: Kira wakes into a muted, domestic morning on an alien world — physically improved, pragmatically grateful, and quietly resigned to the facility's procedures. Her dominant feeling is practical acceptance mixed with small hope: the treatment is working, she can stand, and the alien caretakers (and Buddy/Scout/Remedy) feel less like obstacles and more like companions. That calm is immediately undercut by familiar bureaucratic friction and a rising, low-level worry: forms and dietary assessments stand between her and basic needs (food), and the thought that rescue may not come introduces a thread of dread. The reader experiences a gentle shift from relief/warmth (Kira's recovery, the caretakers' competence and personalities) into wry irritation and anxious impatience as the story reintroduces procedural delays. There are multiple emotional beats — an overall steady acceptance/hope punctuated by frustration and a creeping dread — which mirror the story's established pattern (anticipation/tension → bureaucratic absurdity → pragmatic acceptance), reinforcing the recurring interplay of warm wonder and obstructive procedure rather than breaking it.</reasoning>
        <beats>
          <beat tags="acceptance, hope">POV: Relieved, quietly optimistic and resigned — Kira recognizes tangible improvement (healing pain, better vitals), is able to move, and feels gratitude toward Remedy, Scout, and even the plants. She frames herself in the facility's language to make care happen (acceptance as tactics). Reader: feels relief and warmth at Kira's recovery and the gentle, domestic tone of the scene; there's comfort in the caregiving characters and the sense that immediate danger has abated.</beat>
          <beat tags="frustration, dread">POV: Annoyed and exasperated by the relentless procedural requirements (forms for wound care, dietary assessments) that slow access to basic needs; underlying this is a low but real dread about rescue not arriving soon enough ('If rescue didn't come first. Which seemed increasingly unlikely.'). Reader: experiences wry irritation at the absurdity of bureaucratic delay plus a tightening unease — the comedy of forms coexists with the practical risk (hunger, long-term isolation).</beat>
          <beat tags="hope, wonder">POV: Softening attachment and curious appreciation — Kira notices distinct personalities in Remedy, Holloway, and Scout and allows herself small smiles and emotional connection, even while warning herself that's dangerous. This breeds cautious hope (companionship = reason to keep going) and a muted sense of wonder at living within a breathing facility. Reader: feels a warm, slightly bittersweet uplift as the alien caretakers are humanized, reinforcing emotional investment in Kira's survival and relationships.</beat>
